ce:section.ce:para:
Restricted by intrinsic carbon conjugated structure, most synthesized CDs emit blue light after photoexcitation. Paoprasert group prepared blue or green-emitting CDs using succinic acid and glycerol precursors [23]. The CDs can be used as ferrous ion and hydrogen peroxide dual-mode sensors. The fluorescence of CDs was almost quenched in the presence of H2O2, and then with Fe2+ addition, the emission would recover. The CDs probe demonstrated good selectivity and repeatability. The emission quenching of CDs after H2O2 addition is considered to be caused by PET process. The recovery of emission in the presence of Fe2+ was induced by Fenton effect [24]. They also prepared paper-based CDs sensor for Fe2+ and H2O2 for the first time. The B,N-codoped CDs nano-thermometer devised by Prof. Omer was also used as Fe2+ and Fe3+ sensors through fluorescence quenching response [25]. The limit of detection (LOD) value was 80.0 ± 0.5 nM for Fe2+ and 110.0 ± 0.5 nM for Fe3+. The fluorescence quenching of CDs caused by Fe2+ and Fe3+ was probably due to the formation of stable non-fluorescent complex between iron ion and the functional groups on the surface of CDs. An iron nanoprobe was also exploited for detecting Fe2+ in iron capsules and total iron in serum samples successfully with high reliability (Fig. 1
                           ). Simple citric acid and ethylenediamine were used by Prof. Yang to afford carbonized CDs, and the fluorescence QY was above 80%, comparable to fluorescent molecular dye [26]. Similarly, these CDs also selectively responded to Fe3+. It was postulated that the special coordination between Fe3+ and the hydroxyl groups on the surface of CDs was the reason for dynamic fluorescence quenching that was helpful for the nonradiative electron transfer process including transfer of excited-state electron to the d orbital of Fe3+ 
                           [27]. This fast electron transfer was demonstrated by the shortened fluorescence lifetime. The fluorescence on/off of imaging system containing Fe2+/Fe3+ medium could be modulated via oxidation of Fe2+ into Fe3+. In addition, sodium citrate and manganese dichloride were used as raw materials to prepare blue-emissive photostable CDs. Manganese doping played a crucial contribution to the high fluorescence QY. For Fe3+ sensing, the linear range was 0 500 μM and the LOD value was low to 2.1 nmol/L (turn-off mode) [28]. It was postulated that CDs-Fe3+ pair could facilitate electron/hole recombination annihilation through an efficient and reversible electron/hole transfer process, thus inducing fluorescence quenching.
